text.tspan: 1,234,456 years ago
(give or take a few hundred thousand years)
someone had a cytosine (C) flip to a guanine (G)
at position 23,456,789 on their chromosome 22.
That genetic variant,
which started with that one random person,
has since spread to almost every person on earth.
You've probably inherited a copy of it.
That flip from C to G has little or no effect.
It doesn't make you faster or slower,
smarter or dumber,
stronger or weaker,
more beautiful or uglier.
It sits in one of the many long stretches of human DNA
where a DNA base going this way or that way
makes virtually no difference.
In that way, it's like almost all genetic variants:
No single common genetic variant explains more than 0.2%
of variance in traits like height, intelligence, or mental illness.
As a result, they mostly spread - or fail to spread - randomly.
That random person 1,234,567 years ago had a 50% chance
of passing variant 22_39493049293 on to each of their kids,
who had a 50% chance of passing it on to each of their kids.
That tiny bit of DNA got lucky again and again,
like a coin flip coming up heads again and again,
until nearly everybody on earth back then got a copy of it,
ensuring its survival into the present.
It is one of 183,342 genetic variants found by
the Simons Genome Diversity Project,
the 1000 Genomes Project,
and the Human Genome Diversity Database,
and dated (give or take a few hundred thousand years)
by the _____ Lab at ________.
This video presents all of the genetic variants
that they've found on chromosome 22
and their current geographic distribution.
Why chromosome 22? Because it's short.
You probably wouldn't watch the whole thing
if I did chromosome 1, would you?
If you want to watch it faster or slower,
Youtube lets you adjust the playback speed
by clicking the gear icon.
(I'd suggest turning down the volume if you slow it down.)
Enjoy.
